ABUJA – The pen, as the saying goes, is mightier than the sword. But, how would anyone explain why the mighty have been falling in the midst of COVID-19 battle? In the last seven days, seven Nigerian journalists have died from COVID-19 and other illnesses. Dan Foster died from COVID-19 complications. The seven journalist who have died in the last one week are Dan Foster (Cool FM Radio Station), Hugo Odiogor (former editor at the Vanguard), Xavier Ndayongmong (Crime Editor at Daily Independent), Nkiruka Udoh (Crime and Defence Correspondent at AIT), Naomi Uzor (on the Business Desk at the Vanguard), Aramide Praise Oikelome (the Media Project and Independent Newspapers), and Azeez Ozi Sanni (Cartoonist at The Nation). Nigerian journalists have been facing huge risks and unprecedented challenges as frontline workers covering the coronavirus outbreak and reporting in the newsroom every day. (NewsMakersLive) …Cross River and Kogi Govs must be called to order and their States put on the watch list •L-r: Abdullahi Ganduje of Kano State; Yahaya Bello of Kogi State and Ben Ayade of Cross River State ONITSHA (SundiataPost) - Human rights group, the International Society for Civil Liberties and the… May 10, 2020 In "News" It has been reported that at least 20 journalists have died from the coronavirus outbreak in Peru. According to the Agence France Presse, AFP, most of them infected while reporting on the pandemic, often with little protection, the country’s journalists’ union reported Tuesday. Peru is Latin America’s second worst-hit country… June 3, 2020 In "News" The Federal Government says there is no new case from 61 contacts of the index case of Coronavirus (COVID-19) in the country, NAN reports. The Minister of Health, Osagie Ehanire, at a media update on COVID-19 in Abuja on Friday, said the contacts had been monitored since the announcement of… March 6, 2020 In "Health"